    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense but its still super frustrating. it feels like there's something hidden in the math that's eating my money. is there a specific way to see exactly how much goes to interest vs principal each month so i can track it better?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It is deeply frustrating, and I understand why it feels like some unseen force is hoarding your payment! You can absolutely see this breakdown, and it's not some sneaky, hidden clause—it's just the nature of how the interest accrues. Most loan statements provide an amortization schedule, which is your best friend for this. If your statement doesn't have one, you can usually find a loan calculator online that will generate one for you.\n\nThis schedule will map out every single payment, showing you precisely what percentage and dollar amount is allocated to interest and what is applied to the principal for each month. Seeing that table, month by month, is the best way to track the slow, steady erosion of the interest burden. It's like watching a tiny, persistent line of green (principal payment) slowly push back against a much larger, stubborn line of red (interest charge).\n\nIf you want to speed things up, you could consider making extra payments, which is the most direct way to tackle the principal and starve the interest monster. Even a small, unexpected payment can make a big difference over time.",
      "source": "target",
